{
  "doc_id": "25819",
  "text": "Nutrient sensors evolved as time-giving signals by exerting different actions on the circadian clocks. This is the case of AMPK, regulated by glucose and fatty acids, which directly regulates CRYs proteins [CITATION_1] , CREB, glycogen synthase kinase 3 beta, PPARs, and the redox state [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . One interesting link between sensing of cellular energy status and circadian clocks is the control of clock genes expression and deacetylation of clock proteins by the sirtuins (SIRT), a (NAD + )-dependent class III of histone deacetylases that are well characterized by their numerous effects on intracellular metabolism. Particularly, the SIRT1 and SIRT6 establish functional links between cellular metabolism and circadian clocks physiology in mammals [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The activity of SIRT1 fluctuates through the feeding/fasting cycle [CITATION_6] and is involved in the cyclic control of cofactors and peptides of circadian clocks by deacetylating BMAL1 and PER2 in liver [CITATION_7] and activates the hypothalamic SCN pacemaker in mice [CITATION_8] . The high expression of this enzyme in the ventromedial hypothalamus support the role of this brain area on monitoring metabolic signals through SIRT1, at least in mice. Interestingly, these ventromedial neurons expressing SIRT1 project POMC neurons in the ARC, and innervate the outer shell of SCN, providing a basis to integrate and communicate metabolic signals in the hypothalamus . SIRT6 appears to be involved in the cyclic synthesis of lipids and carbohydrates [CITATION_9] , which may reflect differential responses to distinct nutritional intakes. Whether these molecular sensors modulate brain and peripheral clocks in fish remains to be elucidated. Preliminary studies in rainbow trout assessed changes in mRNA abundance of SIRT-1 in parallel with the functioning of fatty acid sensing systems (Velasco et al., 2016a,b) . The clearly adaptive significance of circadian clocks entrainment by nutrient status is supported in fishes by the feeding-related rhythms driven by the circadian system in digestive enzymes [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Furthermore, changes described in parameters related to glucose, fatty acid, and amino acid metabolism in brain [CITATION_13] and peripheral tissues [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] also support the involvement of nutrient status.",
